<HEAD>Mountaineers Descend after Historic Everest Climb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Climbers from China, Japan and Nepal who staged a
successful rendezvous on Mount Everest's summit were making
progress today in descending the world's tallest peak, the
expedition's leader said.
   When nine of the climbers met on top of the world Thursday, they
achieved two mountaineering firsts: simultaneously scaling Everest
from two sides and making a live telecast from the summit.
   Three other expedition members later reached the summit.
   Shi Zhanchun, the expedition's leader and president of the
Chinese Mountaineering Association, told a news conference that
eight of the climbers who met on the 29,028-foot summit had reached
a camp at 27,224 feet on the north, or Chinese Tibetan, side of the
mountain this morning.
   He said the ninth had descended to 25,551 feet.
   China's official Xinhua News Agency also reported from Katmandu,
Nepal, that Cering Doje of Tibet, Noboru Yamada of Japan and Ang
Lhakpa Sherpa of Nepal reached a camp at 26,174 feet on the south,
or Nepalese, face of Everest.
   The three, who had climbed from the north side, and three others
who made the ascent from the south and were going down the north
face, are attempting to be the first to complete an
across-the-mountain climb.
   Shi said the climbers who met at the summit will not proclaim
victory until they have reached the 21,320-foot level. The descent
is treacherous and there is still danger of climbers suffering
frostbite, he said.
   The expedition is the largest ever to attempt to climb Everest,
with more than 200 people participating. The teams began their
assaults last month.
   Japan's Nihon Television Corp. engineered the alpine telecasts,
which have been beamed by satellite and televised in China, Japan
and Nepal. NTV has paid most of the cost of the $12.5 million
expedition.
   In Tokyo, an NTV spokeswoman said a nine-member group, including
three network cameramen, were scaling the mountain from the
northern side today, while three others climbed from the southern
side.
   She added that more expedition members planned to reach the
summit of the Himalayan peak that straddles the Nepal-China border.
She did not have further details.
   The expedition was staged to honor the 35th anniversary of the
first successful Everest assault, by Sir Edmund Hillary of New
Zealand and Tenzing Norgay, his sherpa guide, on May 29, 1953.
   The conquering of the mountain the Chinese call Qomolangma was
the top news story on television in Beijing and was the lead story,
with large pictures, on the front page of all major dailies today.
   Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping on Thursday telephoned a television
studio to congratulate the ``great pioneers'' of the three nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

