<HEAD>Survivors Describe Death on North America's Highest Peak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of death, climb, other
injuries. ADDS byline. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BARTLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENALI MEDICAL CAMP, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new expedition led by the
first man to conquer Mount McKinley alone in winter ended less than
1,000 feet from the top when one climber apparently froze to death
and three others suffered hypothermia.
   Lynn Salerno, 31, died early Wednesday at the 19,500-foot level
of North America's highest peak, the National Park Service said.
Two other members of the nine-person expedition were evacuated by
helicopter.
   ``We had a beautiful experience turn into a nightmare,'' one
exhausted climber, Leonard Kelly, said as he clutched a hot cup of
tea at Denali Medical Camp at the 14,000-foot level of Mount
McKinley.
   ``It's unbelievable that one minute you can be on top of the
world, and in the next minute under it,'' Kelly said.
   The expedition, which began about May 1, was led by veteran
guide Vern Tejas, who last March became the first mountaineer to
survive a winter climb to McKinley's 20,320-foot summit.
   According to accounts from expedition members, Tejas called a
conference at about 8 p.m. Tuesday, after nearly 10 hours on the
trail. They were still more than 1,000 feet below the summit.
   Tejas warned that the approaching night would be bitterly cold.
He told them to make individual decisions on whether to continue.
   Kelly, at 57 the oldest member of the party, said he had
intestinal cramps and decided to turn back with another man, Dave
Burns. Tejas sent assistant guide John Swider to accompany them to
the 17,200-foot camp. The others, led by Tejas, went on.
   Before the trio reached the haven, Swider fell on the steep,
rocky terrain. He was saved from certain death only when Kelly
secured them using an ice ax.
   ``We all ended up in kind of a blob, hanging on, looking at each
other, because the next step was really kind of a big one _ like a
couple of thousand feet right off the ridge, going straight down,''
Kelly said.
   Other climbers saw the fall and went to the rescue.
   Swider, who had head lacerations and a back injury, and Kelly
were helped back to camp, where they spent a long night worrying
about their companions.
   The others had it even worse.
   Some 500 feet below the summit, Lynn Salerno began acting
irrationally.
   It remains unclear whether she was ailing from hypothermia or
some sort of altitude sickness, but she grew increasingly cold and
unresponsive, the climbers said.
   While others worked desperately to warm her, Tejas tried to dig
a snow shelter in the icy, rocky terrain, but in a matter of
minutes she was dead.
   ``She was such a strong supporter of Vern's,'' Kelly said. ``She
was practically on the trip because of him'' after hearing him
describe his mountain experiences at a talk in Anchorage.
   Kelly was assisted down the mountain Wednesday evening by other
climbers. He was treated for three frostbitten toes.
   Swider and Mike Moss, 50, of Minnesota, who had severely
frostbitten feet, were flown off the mountain to a hospital in
Anchorage.
   Tejas remained with the rest of the expedition at 17,200 feet.
Two reportedly were recovering well from hypothermia.
   ``I felt like we had the best guide in the world,'' Kelly said.
``He did everything in the world a human being could be expected to
do in a dangerous occupation like this.''
</TEXT>
