<HEAD>Handicapped Climber Takes Aim at Tallest Mountain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 21st graf pvs, `The March-through-May...' with graf to
note Sherpa guide Tenzing Norgay was with Hillary on first conquest.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mountaineer Tom Whittaker once hovered
between life and death for 10 days, rallying out of the pain he
incurred in a car accident to persuade doctors to save one of his
feet.
   Nine years later, equipped with a high-tech artificial foot,
Whittaker will join the American Everest Expedition with the goal in
May of becoming the first handicapped climber to conquer the world's
highest peak.
   Watch out if he gets to the top of the world.
   ``That'll blow my drawers off and it will take years to get the
silly grin off my face!'' he laughed.
   Then the man who has devoted his life to helping others overcome
their handicaps addded:
   ``It's a challenge of life as much as a challenge of Everest. You
have to reach deep into yourself to do something like this.''
   Whittaker was driving back to his home in Sun Valley, Idaho, from
a Thanksgiving holiday when an out-of-control car struck his car
head-on. He suffered multiple fractures and damage to both knees.
   ``The original prognosis was they were going to take both feet
off,'' Whittaker, 40, recalled.
   ``I managed to impress on them how important feet are to
mountaineers. I was able to convince them, and they left my foot
intact,'' said Whittaker, who had moved from his native Wales a year
before.
   Surgeons repaired what they could and reconstructed what they
could not of Whittaker's crushed legs. His right foot had to be
amputated, but he still had his left _ and a desire to overcome his
handicap and repay the kindness of a community.
   Before his accident, the mountaineer with expeditions to the
Alps, Spanish Pyrenees and Alaska's Mount McKinley had earned a
master's degree in counseling at Idaho State University and served
as a graduate assistant in an outdoor recreation program.
   The university established a relief fund that helped defray some
of his $30,000 in medical bills not covered by insurance. The school
also provided him with a room and living expenses during the three
months he was bedridden.
   ``I felt I had this debt of gratitude I wanted to pay back to the
community, so I put my master's degree in counseling to work in a
local hospital'' helping others adjust to their handicaps, Whittaker
said in a telephone interview from his Pocatello home.
   While giving a kayaking lesson to a struggling man with a spinal
cord injury, Whittaker noticed tears pouring down the student's face.
   ``I feared I shouldn't have forced him and was trying to blurt
out an apology,'' Whittaker said. ``But he said, `Hey, Whittaker,
you're way off base. You don't need to apologize. This is the first
time I've felt alive in 2{ years.' That basically gives me my
validation for what I do now.''
   Six years ago, he started the university's Cooperative Wilderness
Handicapped Outdoor Group with fewer than 20 students. Today 400 are
enrolled and he lectures throughout the world.
   ``The motto of our group is `Dare to be different.' The whole
idea is to empower people with disabilities and help them with their
personal rehabilitation,'' he explained. ``We're ordinary people
doing stuff; we're not outdoor jocks.
   ``We have children 4 years old, we have disabled people of up to
72 years old in our program _ everybody from kids to grandfathers
and grandmothers.''
   The courage of his students inspired Whittaker, too. Equipped
with an artificial foot fashioned by a blacksmith friend, he
returned to the peaks, climbing Canada's notorious Bugaboos during a
snowstorm in 1981 and scaling the tough north face of Wyoming's
Grand Teton in 1987.
   But until three weeks ago, a shot at conquering Everest was a
dream Whittaker considered out-of-reach. Then came a call from the
Salt Lake City-based American Everest Expedition.
   The March-through-May expedition also includes New Zealand's
Peter Hillary, son of Sir Edmund Hillary. In 1953, the elder Hillary
and the Sherpa guide Tenzing Norgay became the first men to conquer
Everest.
   ``When I was involved in my car accident, all hopes and dreams of
aspiring to Everest died for me,'' Whittaker said. ``When the
telephone rang and (I was) asked if I would like to go ... it just
about knocked me off my stool.''
   Expedition co-leader Peter Athans, of Mt. Kisco, N.Y., said that
while Whittaker will be the first handicapped person to assault
Everest, he ``is a very fit and active guy.''
   Whittaker said if he conquers the mountain it will be on his own
merits, not ``on the backs'' of his teammates.
   San Diego's Daw Co. is designing $40,000 worth of new artificial
feet to enable Whittaker to handle a 150-mile trek over snowfields
to the mountain's base camp and the climb itself.
   ``I don't have to go to the top to have a fullfilling
experience,'' said Whittaker, who conceded high-altitude swelling
and circulation problems with his stump could halt his ascent.
   ``To be successful ... we just have to get one of our (team)
members on the summit. I'm a member of the team. All I need to know
is that I've tried hard and did well.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

