<LEADPARA>  The rolling tremor that shook Southern California today was the kind of
"thrust" earthquake that built the region's mountains, and it probably made
the San Gabriel Mountains a couple of inches taller, a scientist said.;
"The ground moved up in the earthquake," said Lucy Jones, a seismologist with
the U.S. Geological Survey.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  QUAKE PROBABLY MADE MOUNTAINS TALLER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article on page 1A  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The same kind of earthquake was responsible for the Whittier Narrows
earthquake that measured 5.9 on the Richter scale and killed eight people on
Oct. 1, 1987, and for the San Fernando earthquake that measured 6.4 and killed
about five dozen people on Feb. 9, 1971.;    Today's quake measured about 6.0
on the Richter scale and was centered in the San Gabriel Mountains about eight
miles north of Sierra Madre.;    A thrust quake occurs when one block of the
ground moves up and over another block of the ground.;    Scientists suspect
today's quake occurred on the Sierra Madre Fault, which runs along the base of
the San Gabriel Mountains from Upland to San Fernando, almost 50 miles.;    If
the quake did occur on that fault, only a small segment of the fault ruptured
or the quake would have been stronger, Jones said.;    Southern California
straddles the boundary of two great plates that make up Earth's crust -- the
Pacific Plate, which is under the ocean and part of Southern California, and
the North American Plate, which is under the rest of the continent.;    As the
plates slide past each other, quakes occur on numerous "strike-slip" faults,
such as the San Andreas, on which ground slides horizontally past ground on
the other side of the fault.;    But the two gigantic plates also squeeze
together, creating thrust faults and mountains that parallel the Southern
California coast.;    Quakes on such faults built the San Gabriel, San
Bernardino, San Jacinto and Santa Ynez mountains.;    She said the Sierra
Madre Fault has not produced a sizable earthquake in the past 10,000 years.;
 There were roughly 20 to 30 small aftershocks during the first 90 minutes
after the quake, said Egill Hauksson, director of the seismological laboratory
at Caltech.;    Seven of those aftershocks were larger than 2.0 on the Richter
scale, including a magnitude 3.5 jolt at 8:37 a.m., Caltech seismologist Kate
Hutton said.;    The number of aftershocks always is greatest within the first
hours of a big jolt.;    Caltech scientists fanned out into the San Gabriel
Mountains carrying devices that radio precise positions on the ground to
orbiting satellites of the Global Positioning System. That will help them
determine precisely how Earth's surface was deformed during the earthquake,
Jones said.;    Scientists prepared to place a "coffin" -- a large box
containing four seismometers and three strong motion detectors -- on a peak
near Mount Wilson. That will help researchers get detailed information on any
large aftershocks.  </TEXT>
