<HEAD>Authorities Rescue Hikers Trapped on Mount Whitney By Storm</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to UPDATE with identification of victim.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONE PINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers brought more stranded climbers
down from towering Mount Whitney on Sunday, a day after lightning
struck a stone hut and killed one of the 13 hikers seeking shelter
there from a thunderstorm.
   The body of Matthew Nordbrock, 26, of Orange was flown Saturday
from the summit of 14,495-foot Whitney, the tallest mountain in the
contiguous United States, said Ann Melle, Inyo County sheriff's
spokeswoman.
   Four other people who suffered minor injuries, exposure and
burns also were rescued from the mountain Saturday. Three were
treated and released, while the fourth was admitted to Southern
Inyo Hospital in Lone Pine, Ms. Melle said.
   Eight more mountain enthusiasts who had crowded into the 12
feet-by-12 feet cabin were plucked from the mountain by cargo
helicopter about 6 a.m. Sunday. They and two other climbers, who
had made camp at a lower elevation, also were flown to the hospital
for treatment.
   The deadly lightning bolt struck about 3:30 p.m. Saturday in the
middle of a raging thunderstorm. Several hikers raced down from the
summit for help and met someone with a two-way radio, said
sheriff's Lt. Jack Goodrich.
   The frantic radio SOS was intercepted by a jetliner passing
overhead. Pilots notified air traffic controllers at Los Angeles
International Airport and the controllers passed the emergency call
on to Inyo County authorities.
   Rescue efforts began shortly before nightfall. The victim was
pronounced dead at the hospital about an hour after he was brought
in.
   The stone structure the hikers packed into was built in 1909 for
astronomers. It is not recommended as a shelter.
   ``The hut at the top is not there for hikers,'' Ms. Melle said.
``It's just an old, old structure. This is back country area.
Anyone who is up here is expected to be prepared. Mountain tops are
dangerous places to be.''
   Authorities had no plans to close the trail, Ms. Melle said.
   ``Mount Whitney is known for unusual storms,'' she said. ``It's
a very severe peak. Bad weather conditions are expected and weather
forecasts had predicted bad conditions.''
   Ms. Melle said up to 300 people attempt to scale the mountain
each day during the busy summer climbing season. Experienced
mountaineers usually take two days to hike the roughly 16 miles to
Mount Whitney's summit from the trailhead at 9,000 feet, near Lone
Pine.
   The mountain's majestic peak can be seen for miles along the
eastern Sierra Nevada range.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

