<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   On Sports: Fifty States of Exaltation
   ----
   By Frederick C. Klein
</HL>
<DATE>
08/23/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<LP>
   I generally do not cheer my countrymen's penchant for
turning pastimes into manias, but one has come to my
attention that I think deserves at least polite applause.
It's called "highpointing," and it's nothing less than the
pursuit of the highest ground in all 50 of these United
States.
   Highpointing combines the joys and athleticism of mountain
hiking with whimsy and moments of sheer terror. The whimsy
comes mostly because the peaks of some of our flatter states
are not peaks at all but merely bumps that are a bit higher
than surrounding bumps, and their challenge isn't so much in
the climbing as in the finding.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The terror, of course, can occur at moments when, on
climbs of even modest difficulty, a foothold crumbles or a
chasm must be traversed. "You can find air under your butt in
unexpected places," says Don Holmes, an engineer from La
Mirada, Calif., who has bagged 44 high points. "That's what
makes the whole thing interesting."
   To date, 19 individuals have the distinction of having
conquered all 50. They're a diverse lot, ranging in age of
achievement from 22 years old to more than 70, and in
residence from the stately Rocky Mountain states to such
plain and plainlike ones as Oklahoma and Missouri. Two of
them are women, including the latest to make the list. She's
Donna Allsup, a school administrator from Little Rock, Ark.
   One man, Adrian Crane of Modesto, Calif., negotiated his
50 in a 101-day blitz. Another, and more sensible, fellow,
Jack Parsell of Beaver Falls, N.Y., savored the experience by
allowing 50 years to elapse between his first and his 50th.
   Almost a score of others have 40 or more high points to
their credit and, thus, are within striking distance of 50.
They include the wife and two sons of Jack Bennett, an Ohioan
who has reached the 50 mark. They do not include Shatz, the
German shepherd dog of the above-mentioned Mrs. Allsup, who
is said to have climbed 40.
   "What we have in common, I guess, is that we're
list-makers and recordkeepers," says Jack Longacre of
Mountain Home, Ark., who not only has bagged all 50 but
started an organization, called -- naturally -- the
Highpointers Club, which encourages the pursuit. Its
membership now exceeds 400.
   He adds: "It's a frequent accusation that we're also a bit
nuts. I don't think that's true in my own case, but I can't
vouch for everyone in our group."
   One other thing that highpointers share is access to
wheels, because getting to some states' peaks is a lot more
trouble than mounting them. According to Don Holmes's book
"Highpoints of the United States," a guide to the lofty 50
published by Cordillera Press of Evergreen, Colo., 16 can be
reached most easily by auto (Delaware's, elevation 442 feet,
is at a road intersection), and a dozen others require little
more than a walk of a few hundred yards through some woods or
across a field.
   "In a few states, including Iowa, Missouri, North Dakota
and Oklahoma, the high points are on private property, and
the owners like you to get their permission before entering,"
Holmes notes. "That's usually no problem, though, because
they're in such remote places that they're glad for the
company."
   This does not mean that the lesser high points are pieces
of cake. Indiana's, for example, lacks a definitive marker,
and while guide books can direct hikers to the proper field,
the exact summit (elevation 1,257 feet) can be elusive. A
group of Highpointers Club members dragged surveying gear
around the site for a day last April in an effort to nail it
down.
   (Some, however, are quite easy to find. Iowa's is on a
cattle-feeding trough on a farm in Osceola County, and the
farmer has put an expired license plate reading "HIGH PT" on
the structure's roof.)
   At the other extreme are six peaks whose conquest requires
technical mountaineering skill and more than a bit of luck
with the weather. That list includes Mount Hood in Oregon,
Mount Rainier in Washington, Granite Peak in Montana, Gannett
Peak in Wyoming, Borah Peak in Idaho and Mount McKinley in
Alaska.
   The last, at 20,320 feet the highest on the North American
continent, is the toughest, hands down. It's a windswept,
32-mile trek over snow, ice and rock that usually takes about
three weeks in weather that can change for the much-worse
with little warning. The success rate is estimated at 50%,
and only the most intrepid climbers try it. Backpacker
magazine summarizes its difficulty as follows: "Do it right
or die."
   The 53-year-old Longacre, who in 1983 climbed the big
mountain that's called "Denali" by local Indians, elaborates:
"It's the cold and nearness to the Arctic Circle that makes
Denali a killer; the air seems thinner at 20,000 feet there
than at 24,000 feet in other parts of the world. I'm
sometimes asked how it can be verified that people who say
they climbed all the high points really did it. The answer is
simple: Everybody in climbing knows who's done Denali. And if
you've done it, there's no need to lie about any of the
rest."
   But Longacre continues that even if Mount McKinley is
beyond a person's reach -- and it certainly is for many --
highpointing still can be rewarding. "In between Denali and
those silly ones in the Midwest are some beautiful climbs
that ordinary people in good physical condition can
accomplish with no special difficulty. Mount Rogers in
Virginia, on the Appalachian Trail, is one. Guadalupe Peak in
Texas is another {I know] I climbed it]} Mount Elbert in
Colorado is a third. Some of my best days have been spent in
places like those."
   Jerry Wagener, a computer scientist who lives in Tulsa,
Okla., agrees; last year he and his son, Jeff, became the
first father-son team to complete the 50. Jerry was 53 years
old at the end of the two-and-a-half year effort, Jeff was
22.
   "We got a thrill out of climbing McKinley, sure, but just
being up on any real mountain, anywhere, nearly matches it,"
says he. "That whole period when Jeff and I were climbing
together was the high point of my life."
   I don't think he intended any pun.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

