<HEAD>Frenchmen Climb Mount Everest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Frenchman who already holds the record
for the fastest ascent of Mount Everest has climbed the world's
tallest mountain again with two compatriots, the Tourism Ministry
said.
   A ministry statement said Marc Batard, a 39-year-old alpine
guide, reached the top of the 29,028-foot mountain Friday through
the traditional southeast ridge.
   The statement, citing a radio message from the base camp, said
Batard was accompanied by Pascal Tour Naire, a 40-year-old
photographer, and the team physician, Christin Janin, 32.
   Five hours before the three men reached the top, another
Frenchman, Eric de Camp, 35, and two Nepalese Sherpa guides reached
the peak.
   Batard had climbed the Everest in 1988 in 22 hours, the fastest
ascent ever by a mountaineer. It was not known how long he took to
reach the peak Friday.
</TEXT>
