<HEAD>Another Hillary Conquers World's Highest Peak</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, `Peter Hillary...' to CORRECT spelling of
mountaineer; Subs penultimate graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with more
climbers reaching summit, picking up trash left by others.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of the man who first climbed
Mount Everest reached the peak of the world's highest mountain
today, following an American team and members of a three-nation
peace climb to the crowded summit.
   Peter Hillary, son of mountaineer Edmund Hillary, reached the
top of the 29,029-foot peak 37 years after his father and sherpa
guide Tenzing Norgay pioneered the way. It was his fourth attempt.
   Hillary, 36, followed the traditional southeastern route first
used by his father. He reached the top at 7:30 a.m. with the two
leaders of an eight-member New Zealand team, their base camp
reported by radio. The message said the trio was accompanied by a
Nepalese sherpa guide, Apa Sherpa, 33.
   ``It's been a bit of a struggle over the years, but we're
thrilled to bits that you're finally standing on top of the old
mountain,'' Sir Edmund told Peter by satellite telephone from
Auckland.
   Hillary said it had been a long, hard morning and he was feeling
``absolutely over the moon'' at reaching the summit.
   ``It's very, very cold up here. I've been having difficulty
keeping some of my extremities, my hands warm so I'm going to be
heading down as soon as I can,'' he said.
   The team aimed to return to the South Col camp, about 3,000 feet
from the summit on the south side of the mountain.
   Most of the climbers were using oxygen.
   Sir Edmund was made a knight of the British Empire for his
exploit four decades ago. He has retained a long association with
Nepal and has led aid projects there, building schools and
hospitals to improve the lives of the Sherpa people.
   His wife and daughter were killed in a plane crash in Nepal in
1975.
   Since Sir Edmund reached the summit of Mount Everest, many
climbers have followed in his footsteps. Their expeditions have
left behind an estimated two tons of trash, including empty oxygen
bottles and cans. The summit, which can handle only about 20
climbers at a time, is sometimes nearly crowded.
   Minutes before the younger Hillary completed his feat today,
five Americans _ three lawyers, a geologist and a mountain guide _
reached the peak, the Nepalese Tourism Ministry said.
   The five Americans were members of an 11-member team that also
followed the traditional southeastern route.
   The American climbers are Peter George Alhams, a 32-year-old
mountain guide from Snow Bird, Utah; Dana Quentin Coffield, a
31-year-old geologist from Columbia, S.C.; and lawyers Glenn
Porzak, 41, of Boulder, Colo.; Michael Browning, 37, of Manitou
Springs, Colo.; and Brent Manning, 39, of Salt Lake City. They were
accompanied by two Nepalese Sherpa guides, the ministry said.
   Meanwhile, a Belgian Everest expedition abandoned its attempt on
the same route Thursday after the regulator of an oxygen cylinder
burst, the ministry said.
   On April 24, five members of a Nepalese army expedition climbed
Everest.
   And three days ago, climbers from a three-nation team _ the
United States, China and the Soviet Union _ scaled Everest from its
northern side through Tibet. Six climbers in the fourth and last
group from the expedition reached the summit today, China's
official news agency reported. Included in the group was American
Mark Scott Tucker. There was no hometown listed for Tucker.
   The climbers have been filling duffle bags with garbage left by
previous expeditions and taking it back down the mountain.
   Expeditions from Switzerland and Australia are still on the
mountain, waiting in line for a chance to reach the top.
</TEXT>
