<HEAD>In Nepal, a Mountain of Paperwork Comes Before the Mountain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is the very picture of adventure, the
climber planting a flag in triumph atop an icy Himalayan peak. What
isn't generally known, however, is that a mountain of paperwork has
to be scaled first.
   Mountain climbing in Nepal, for all its risk and romance, also
means conquering an array of permits, payments, insurance forms,
and wills for Sherpa guides. And then comes patience, for it can
take years to get it all done.
   Anyone who wants to climb the famed Mount Everest, for example,
may have to wait six or seven years to get a Nepalese government
permit because the world's highest peak also is Nepal's most
desired challenge. Then there are the expenses and 58 pages of
rules set down by Nepal's government.
   ``Probably 80 percent of the effort is getting to the bottom of
the mountain (to start the climb),'' says Steve Langley, a Canadian
leading a six-week expedition up 22,479-foot Mount Ama Dablam, 10
miles southwest of Everest.
   Langley, a 40-year-old computer consultant from Calgary,
Alberta, first applied to climb the mountain in 1982.
   ``We arrived here without the permit,'' he said. ``It was
finally granted officially three weeks ago.''
   Murari P. Khatiwada of Nepal's Mountaineering Division says the
long wait is due to the growing number of people who want to ascend
122 of the 1,310 peaks Nepal grants permits for.
   ``Ten years ago we had 20 expeditions throughout the year. Now
we have more than 100,'' said Khatiwada.
   He explained that amounted to 800 to 1,000 climbers, not
including the guides and porters, usually from the nimble Sherpa
tribe, who accompany foreign mountaineers.
   For this reason, Khatiwada said, nearly all Nepal's mountains
are booked through 1990 and applications for some peaks are being
accepted for the year 2000.
   He said it was vital to limit the number of climbers to protect
Nepal's environment.
   ``A mountain is fragile,'' he explained. ``It cannot bear the
burden of too many people.''
   Just as frustrating as the wait for climbers are the government
regulations, which get down to such details as how many socks,
shoes and umbrellas must be supplied to guides and porters. They
also list fees for the peaks. All that is just the beginning of an
expedition's expenses.
   The permit to climb Everest's 29,028 feet costs $2,547. For any
other peak above 26,400 feet, the fee is $2,038. For Mount Ama
Dablam, it costs $1,528.
   Langley's team of himself, four other Canadians and an American
has budgeted $24,000 for the climb, and he said ``we're doing it on
the cheap.''
   All his people are experienced and already have most of the
needed equipment. The American climber, Tom Dickey, 31, of Boulder,
Colo., has worked as a trekking guide in Nepal.
   But the team is taking along a liaison officer, required by the
government but paid by the expedition; a chief Sherpa; an
assistant, and 12 porters. Salaries for all are specified in the
government rules, along with the equipment to be provided them.
   Langley said the actual gear is rarely given the Sherpas, most
of whom have equipment from earlier climbs, and a cash payment is
usually negotiated in lieu of equipment.
   ``The daily salary, in the scheme of things, is peanuts,'' said
Langley.
   He said the pay to the government liaison officer, for example,
is $2 a day. His equipment allowance comes to the equivalent of
$800.
   Other expenses include $1,000 for an agency to help ease the way
through the Nepalese bureaucracy, $350 for required insurance for
climbers and Sherpas, and the cost of getting climbers and their
equipment to Nepal.
   Each man on Langley's team is putting up $4,000 to make the
climb, although expeditions often seek funds from mountaineering
societies, philanthropists or companies wanting publicity for their
products.
   Peter Hill, an Englishman also leading an expedition up Ama
Dablam, said he wrote 400 letters seeking backing without success.
   ``To get money these days for a peak, it's got to be unclimbed
or it's got to be Everest,'' he complained.
   But Hill, 26, ran into a stroke of luck. His father happened
upon a newspaper ad for a bank, Perpetual Unit Trust, picturing its
symbol _ the peak of Ama Dablam.
   Dickey, the Colorado climber, noted that mountaineers can avoid
all the preliminary trouble by climbing Europe's Alps or the Andes
in South America, where no permits are needed.
   Nevertheless, he said, ``I'm in on an Everest expedition in
1990.''
</TEXT>
