<HEAD>Son Of Famed Sherpa Guide Will Join Climb Marking First Assault On
Everest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of one of first two men to conquer Mount
Everest has set his own sights on the mighty mountain, joining a
team that hopes to scale the world's highest peak to mark the 35th
anniversary of the feat.
   Tenzing Norbu, a Connecticut travel agent and the son of Tenzing
Norgay, said he joined the expedition to honor his late father, the
Sherpa guide who joined New Zealander Edmund Hillary at the top of
the world in 1953.
   ``For me, it is a pilgrimage to a mountain which has reshaped
the lives of my family and my people,'' Tenzing, 25, said at a news
conference Wednesday.``It will allow me to pay homage to my late
father.''
   The young Tenzing, a University of New Hampshire graduate who
works for a travel agency in Westport, Conn., only will go as far
as the base camp, about 17,000 feet, on the Chinese Tibetan side of
the mountain that straddles the Nepal-China border.
   The final assault on the summit of the 29,028-feet peak, the
world's highest, will be made by an international team of
mountaineers led by Robert Anderson, 30, a Denver native now living
in Auckland, New Zealand.
   Anderson, joined by two other Americans and a British climber,
will attempt to reach the peak without oxygen by an untried route
along the eastern side of the mountain.
   Like the Nepalese Tenzing and Hillary in 1953, the ``Everest
'88'' expedition will be supported by the United Nations. Miklos
Pinther, chief cartographer of the U.N. Secretariat, will travel to
the base camp and the climbers will have a U.N. flag to plant on
the summit.
   The group leaves Beijing on Thursday for Lhasa, the capital of
Tibet. From there, they will begin a five-day journey accompanied
by 45 yaks to a site where they will set up their base camp.
   Anderson, who came within 800 feet of the summit in a 1985
expedition to Everest, said the team hopes to put a man at the peak
by the end of April.
   He said the climbers will forgo oxygen to relive some of the
challenge of the original assault, much of which has been
diminished by technological advances in climbing equipment. Tenzing
and Hillary used oxygen in their climb.
   The young Tenzing said he will give the summit assault team
objects similar to those his father took up the mountain, including
a wooden black cat, a broken pencil and candy to pay respect to the
mountain gods.
   Tenzing and Hillary reached the summit on May 29, 1953. Since
then, 209 people have conquered the mountain, but only about 15
without oxygen, according to Anderson.
   Tenzing Norgay, the ``tiger of the snows,'' died in May 1986 at
the age of 72 in Darjeeling, India, where he set up a climbing
school. Hillary, now Sir Edmund, is New Zealand's ambassador to
India. The two men kept their vow never to reveal which first set
foot on the majestic pinnacle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

