<HEAD>Sleep Disruption Blamed For Mountain Climbers' Impaired Judgment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mountain climbers may suffer impaired
judgment because they don't sleep well, according to a study of six
people who simulated climbing Mount Everest by living 40 days in a
low-pressure chamber.
   ``People have known for a long time that sleep at high altitudes
is poor. We found sleep at high altitudes is so poor that little
restorative effect can be expected,'' Dr. James D. Anholm said in a
summary of his study.
   ``These new results call into question the long-held belief that
the dangers of high-altitude climbing are due primarily to the
dangers of terrain, weather and the lack of oxygen,'' Anholm said.
   Oxygen lack at night, instead of during the day's exertions,
probably is responsible for the severe sleep loss, said Anholm, an
assistant professor of medicine at Loma Linda University Medical
Center in California.
   Climbers who carry oxygen at high altitudes would probably
benefit more from using it while they sleep than while they are
awake, he said.
   Jim Whittaker, who in 1963 became the first American to reach
the summit of Everest, the world's tallest mountain at more than
29,000 feet, was skeptical of the study but said it may have merit.
   ``It could be lack of sleep causes people to make mistakes at
high altitudes, but I think it's more the lack of oxygen'' during
exertion, he said by telephone from Port Townsend, Wash. ``I feel
that's a bigger cause. You don't sleep a lot, but you sleep
enough.''
   Phil Ershler, who in 1984 became the first American to climb
Everest's north face, said he sleeps well on mountains, but ``I
don't think there's any question that there's some validity'' to
Anholm's conclusions.
   How well a climber sleeps and performs at high altitude ``is
very much an individual thing,'' Ershler said by phone from
Bellevue, Wash.
   Anholm, an internist, presented his study in May at the
Federation of American Societies for Experimental Biology annual
meeting here.
   The six people in Anholm's study were among eight paid
volunteers who lived for 40 days in a large low-pressure chamber in
Natick, Mass., as part of a larger Army-funded study of the effects
of high altitude.
   Pressures in the chamber were regularly reduced to simulate a
climb of Everest, with stops at sea level, 15,000 feet, 20,000 feet
and 26,410 feet, about the level of the South Col camp.
   Anholm measured oxygen in the volunteers' blood and monitored
their sleep by measuring brain waves.
   He found blood oxygen levels were lowest at high altitude and
during sleep, and that as altitude increased, the volunteers slept
much less, awakened more often, felt more irritable in the morning,
and had far more frequent episodes of sleep apnea, intervals during
which breathing ceased for about 10 seconds.
   Even at the simulated 15,000-foot level, the volunteers rarely
slept more than 10 minutes before awakening. Most significantly,
the number of arousals _ two- or three-second awakenings that
weren't remembered, as opposed to full awakenings that last more
than 10 seconds _ rose from 20 per hour at sea level to 117 per
hour at 26,410 feet.
   ``For sleep to have a restorative effect, it needs to be
relatively undisturbed,'' Anholm said. ``These very brief arousals
disturb sleep enough that you perform as though you are partially
sleep deprived.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 30</NOTE>
</DOC>

